Time Series Regression Model for Consumer Price Index of Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco¶

Alkım Can Çelik¶
2018402222¶

Introduction¶

In this assignment, the consumer price index of alcoholic beverages and tobaccos will be analyzed. As opposed to most products, the prices of these products are fixed, especially for the cigarettes. The prices of alcohols vary very slightly which can be ignored. It is widely known that the proportion of taxes in the prices is very large, therefore, the changes in prices are generally determined by the government, not by the producers themselves. As it will be seen from the plots, there are sudden increases in the price due to the additional taxes. The reasons, including having a conservative government, for these rises are open to discuss.

In this homework, the quantitative reasons will be explored. Since most of the alcohols are imported, the exchange rate will be put into the discussion. In addition, the consumer confidence index is more related to the political view of the topic. As mentioned above, since the prices are determined mostly by the taxes, this variable may be helpful for the model. Also, the search volume of keyword "sigaraya zam" will be added as a feature. It may be helpful to detect the sudden changes in the CPI. Lastly, if there is a seasonality behavior, time related variables will be used because it is a time series data and residuals may include some autocorrelations, which should be eliminated.

The plot is below.

In [51]:
ggplot(alc_tob_cpi ,aes(x=Date,y=CPI)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(se=FALSE) + 
ggtitle("Consumer Price Index of Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco") + ylab("CPI (TL)")

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

It is obvious that CPI has increased exponentially and the variance of it has been increasing. At some points, it increased suddenly and stayed steady for a some amount of time. This behavior exists mainly throughout the period, and it may cause some autocorrelation problems in the model. The reason of this behavior is that prices of alcohols and tobaccos are steady in general. They are generally fixed and they get raise one time in a year generally. Between 2017 and 2019, the CPI values stayed almost same, then it increased almost 50%. There are also strange observations, such as, in middle of 2019, the CPI changed almost in every month.

There is no seasonality in the data, which means the time-related features do not seem to be necessary. Also, there are some outliers in the data. CPI values may need to be transformed, but it will be done later because the model performance without the transformation should be seen at first.

Now, since it is a non-stationary time series data, trend factor should be added, instead of moving average trend.

In [52]:
alc_tob_cpi = data.table(alc_tob_cpi)
alc_tob_cpi[,trend:=1:.N]

It can be seen that trend seems statistically significant in this linear regression model, as expected. Adjusted R-squared is very high. Although this high adjusted R-squared value means a good fit, when the residuals and their distribution are checked, it does not give the intended results. Firstly, from the residuals vs. fitted graph, residuals seem to have a nonlinear relationship, rather than linear, which violates the main linearity assumption in linear regression. Secondly, residuals display a seasonal pattern and there is not random distribution on zero mean value. Patterns should have not been in the residual graph. Thirdly, autocorrelation in the residuals is quite high, according to Breusch-Godfrey test. Fourthly and lastly, residuals do not have good normal distribution. These problems will be handled one by one.

Now, firstly, since CPI has increased exponentially, and residuals have a nonlinear relationship with fitted values, another model can be constructed by taking the logarithm of CPI.

In [54]:
alc_tob_cpi[,log_CPI:=log(CPI)]

ggtitle("Logarithm of Consumer Price Index of Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco") + ylab("log(CPI (TL))")

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Now, the transformed CPI values seem to be more suitable for the time series regression models. The exponential growth is eliminated here. This transformation can be interpreted easily.

Now, consumer confidence index will be added.

Consumer Confidence Index¶

The Consumer Confidence Index (CCI) is a survey that measures how optimistic or pessimistic consumers are regarding their expected financial situation. This index may reflect the political side of these price changes. Since the prices are determined by the government, it may be negatively correlated with CPI. However, since the data are based on surveys from citizens, the data may not be reliable because the people attending to the survey may be chosen by the government itself, which means the data may be biased.

Now, we will apply the same data operations made above.

It may be helpful for explaining the sudden increases in the price of tobaccos and alcohols because when there is a "zam", it is searched in Google generally to learn the new prices. Since there has not been no decrease in prices, the word of "zam" should be better, rather than "indirim".

Lag-1 (Autoregressive) Variable¶

Now, the CPI of previous month will be added as a feature into the model.

In [75]:
alc_tob_cpi$log_lag_1 <- as.numeric(sapply(1:nrow(alc_tob_cpi), function(x) alc_tob_cpi$log_CPI[x-1]))
#Since the data are shifted by 1, January-2012 lag-1 variable is NA
                                #It is filled with the next lag-1 variable, February 2012
alc_tob_cpi <- alc_tob_cpi %>% fill(log_lag_1, .direction = "up")

The model will be constructed by using both trend and lag-1 variables.

It can be easily realized that the model performance is increased. Trend, the search volume, and lag-1 CPI variables are statistically significant. The interesting observation is that the USD-TRY exchange rate is no longer statistically significant. The reason is that autoregressive variables dominate the other variable in theory. It can be proven from the coefficients of the independent variables. The exchange rate may be removed from the model, but the model will not be probably improved much. Adjusted R-squared value is almost 1, which is suspicious. When the residuals are compared to fitted values, it can be seen that residuals seem to have linear relationship with fitted values and they are generally negative, which means the predictions are usually higher then the actual observations. The randomness in residuals is incresaed compared to the models above.

The reason of such an increment in the performance is that prices of cigarettes and alcohols are "sticky" in short run. When their prices are increased, they have the same price in a long period, approximately one year. Using lag-1 variable gives an intuition that the price will be probably the same on the next month.

To verify the model, we need to see the autocorrelation graphs.

	Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of order up to 10

data:  Residuals
LM test = 6.9254, df = 10, p-value = 0.7325

According to Breusch-Godfrey test, we fail to reject null hypothesis, which is that there is no autocorrelation in residuals. There are some peaks in residuals, which occur on the month which the prices of the products get a rise. The model cannot easily detect the sudden increases, as expected. In addition, residuals almost have a normal distribution, but there are some outliers which result in some distortions in the distribution. They may be removed at the final model. Autocorrelation in residuals seems to be eliminated now.

It is interesting that the highest correlation exists between CPI and the exchange rate although the rate is not significant in the final model. The reason is that they both have an upward trend. Especially, in the last 2 years, they both increased much. However, the search volume is helpful only when a sudden increase in prices happens. Therefore, the correlation between CPI and the search volume is low.

It can be seen that predictions are very close to the actual observations. The leading reason for this situation is to have autoregressive variable in the model because CPI has not shown a random distribution since 2012. As mentioned above, the prices are sticky in the short run. The price on next month will be probably very close to the current price. Another reason is given above, which is that autoregressive variables may reduce the other variables' effects on the dependent variable.

Conclusion¶

  • Consumer price index (CPI) of alcohols and tobaccos have an upward trend in the long run. Therefore, the variables having a similar trend seem to be statistically significant.
  • CPI does not change in a some period, generally 1 year, in other words, prices are "sticky" in the short run.
  • Since the prices are highly affected by the taxes, and sticky in the short run, they jump to the new level after this period and stay there.
  • There is no monthly or yearly seasonal behavior.
  • The exchange rate has a high correlation with CPI, but it is not a significant independent variable in the model.
  • The search volume of "sigaraya zam" is very informative about the sudden jumps in CPI.
  • The price of previous month is the most significant dependent variable in the model. The reasons are that the prices are generally steady, and autoregressive variables dominates the other independent variables. The price at the next month will be probably very close to the price at current month.
  • Consumer confidence index does not affect CPI significantly.
